At https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/master/graphene/types/argument.py#L28
```py
def __eq__(self, other):
    return isinstance(other, Argument) and (
        self.name == other.name,
        self.type == other.type,
        self.default_value == other.default_value,
        self.description == other.description
    )
```
will always be true in boolean context if `isinstance(other, Argument)`, since the other condition is a tuple of four bools which is truthy no matter the value of the bools. I think what was meant is
```py
def __eq__(self, other):
    return isinstance(other, Argument) and all(
        self.name == other.name,
        self.type == other.type,
        self.default_value == other.default_value,
        self.description == other.description
    )
```
or
```py
def __eq__(self, other):
    return isinstance(other, Argument) and (
        self.name == other.name and
        self.type == other.type and
        self.default_value == other.default_value and
        self.description == other.description
    )
```

